l name from Middle Low German <i>bade</i> ‘messenger’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"von","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Ivo  , derived from the oblique case of the name."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes von Baden was born in 1250, in Baden, her father, Hermann VI. von Baden Markgraf von Verona und Baden, was 26 and her mother, Gertraud Von Babenberg, was 24. She married Count Ulrich III von Heunburg. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1295, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1250–1295":"1250–1295","1249–1268":"1249–1268","1244–1308":"1244–1308","1268–1292":"1268–1292","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1225–1291":"1225–1291","1226–1288":"1226–1288","24 April 1288":"24. aprill 1288","4 October 1291":"4. oktoober 1291","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","8 DEC 1292":"8. detsember 1292","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1248":"1248","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1268":"1268","1288":"1288","1244":"1244","ung. 1290":"umbes 1290","1308":"1308","Feuersberg bei  Globasnitz, Unterkärnten, Österr